, and explains why race continues to generate controversy as a tool of classification even in our genomic age.Surveying the work of some of the twentieth century's most notable scientists, Race Unmasked reveals how genetics and related biological disciplines formed and preserved ideas of race and, at times, racism. A gripping history of science and scientists, Race Unmasked elucidates the limitations of a racial worldview and throws the contours of our current and evolving understanding of human diversity into sharp relief.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness & EconomicsxInfrastructure. 0aEugenicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman biologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman biologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopulation geneticszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial SciencexGeneral. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aVenter, J. Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenter, J. Craig.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/yude1687440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537995.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK